				</figure>
			</div>



	



		<p>Fashion lovers are constantly being tempted to shop: Blogs, Instagram feeds, magazines, Pinterest, catalogs, TV commercials, email newsletters ... just about every form of media we consume urges us to buy, buy, buy. And with dozens of fast fashion companies churning out $5 tee shirts and $25 pairs of jeans, shopping for clothing, shoes, and accessories has become a relatively inexpensive past-time for many.</p>
<div id="adsense1" adsense-numlinks="3" adsense-displaylabel="true" class="adsense-slot adsense ads-half"></div>

	
		<div id="radlinks3" data-num-links="5" data-character-limit="null" data-display-label="false" data-display-inline="true" class="radlinks ads-half"></div>
	

		<p class="cb-split"> And if you&#39;ve got lots of flexibility with your disposable income, that can feel great.</p><p>But if you&#39;re a mom with a mortgage or a grad student living on ramen or really anyone for whom money is tight, creating and following a clothing budget can help ensure that you make sound spending decisions.</p><h3>Factors to consider</h3><p>Before we dive in to hard numbers, let&#39;s explore why there won&#39;t be a single budget parameter that works for every woman on earth.</p>
<div id="inArticleVideo" data-defer="onPageLoad"></div>
		<p class="cb-split"> Aside from total personal income, geography, and availability of clothing - all of which are key factors - there&#39;s the fact that some women need more clothing than others.</p><p>Now wait, hear me out.</p><p>If you are a corporate lawyer and mom of two, you need a set of clothes for work and a set of clothes for home. If you live in Chicago, you need clothing for three seasonal temperature ranges: Moderate, freezing, and oppressively hot. If you&#39;re single and you work at a doggy day care in the temperate Pacific northwest, one set of clothing may suffice. If your office is business casual and that aligns with your personal style, work wear and weekend wear may overlap completely.Â </p><p>Just about everyone needs special occasion wear for weddings and parties, gym clothes, and seasonal garments.</p>
<div id="adsense2" adsense-numlinks="2" adsense-displaylabel="true" class="adsense-slot adsense ads-half"></div>

		<p class="cb-split"> But while some women need to maintain several complete wardrobes at once, others can make do with one. If you consistently dress for a variety of formality levels, your annual clothing budget may need to be larger than that of a person who sticks to just one.</p><h3>How much do most people spend on clothing each year?</h3><p>SO hard to nail down, friends.</p>

		<p class="cb-split"> <a href="http://www.bls.gov/spotlight/2012/fashion/" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" data-ordinal="1">A 25-year-long study run from 1985 to 2015 showed that most households spent between $1,500 and $1,800 per year on clothing</a>. And although it lumps all family members together for those overarching stats, the same study pointed out that the largest chunk of that money was spent on clothing for women aged 16 and over. More recent numbers from the Bureau of Labor Statistics estimate <a href="http://www.bls.gov/news.release/cesan.nr0.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" data-ordinal="2">most households spent an average of $1,786 in 2014</a>. But these are averages that may not apply if you are unmarried, don&#39;t have any kids, or have lots of kids and/or grandkids. These are also statistics that pertain to American families, and may feel inaccurate if you live elsewhere. They do, however, provide a baseline that many experts use to determine an appropriate and prudent clothing budget.</p><h3>How much is reasonable?</h3><p>Again, this will vary. But instead of landing on a hard number, many people prefer to set a clothing budget based on percentage of income. <a href="http://petetheplanner.com/ideal-budget-2/" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" data-ordinal="3" rel="nofollow">Award-winning financial planner Pete Dunn suggests allotting 5% of your income for clothing</a>. (And we&#39;re talking take-home pay, here, not gross.) He points out that fashionistas may find this percentage impossible to handle, but points out that having a budget in place will be extremely helpful regardless. Dunn offers a complete budget breakdown, and depending on your situation, you could scoot some of his suggested percentages around a bit to give your clothing budget a bit more leeway.</p><p>Personal finance company <a href="http://www.learnvest.com/knowledge-center/budgeting-for-work-clothing-what-percent-of-net-income/" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" data-ordinal="4" rel="nofollow">LearnVest is even more conservative, suggesting 4% of take-home pay be spent on clothing, shoes, and accessories</a>.</p><p><a href="https://www.unionplus.org/money-credit/budgeting-tips" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" data-ordinal="5" rel="nofollow">Money Management International, a nonprofit consumer-counseling organization, gives a little more wiggle room, suggesting between 3% and 10%</a>, and most financial planners offer a similar range. I&#39;ve never seen any budgeting of finance expert give the thumbs up to more than 10%.</p><h3>How can I find budget parameters that work for ME?</h3><p>First off, start tracking your clothing-related spending. You may be way off and dumping 25% of your income into the mall, or you may be spot-on at 4% or 5%. Adjust your budget accordingly and see how it impacts your finances overall. If doing 4% makes you miserable and you&#39;re able to meet your savings goals by allotting 7% to clothing, go for it. If you&#39;re already at 4% and still struggling, might I suggest <a href="http://shoppingtips.about.com/od/secondhandshopping/ss/Fashion-Classics-That-You-Can-and-Should-Buy-Secondhand.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="6">thrifting</a>? Use these numbers as simple suggestions, and make your own personalized adjustments as needed. After all, you&#39;re the boss of your money. And your wardrobe.</p>

	
	
	

</article>

